summary.pers_doc: For most states, COVID-19 new cases hit the peak between 2020-Nov and 2021-Jan and drop significantly in 2021-Mar. In the following order of cluster numbers: 5-1-7-3-6-2-4, the later cluster number is, the bigger that the number of new covid cases is after 2020-Nov. California, Texas, Florida have relatively big amount of new cases after 2020-Nov while states like Alaska, Oregon etc., have relatively small amount of new cases during that period. Beyond of that, when comparing number of new cases in 2020-Oct and 2020-Nov with that in 2020-Dec and 2021-Jan, cluster 4 hit peak later than other clusters, which was in 2020-Dec, while Cluster 7 hit peak earlier in 2020-Oct, other clusters are in-between.

For entertainment attendance, in most states, entertainment attendance hit low in 2020-Apr but gradually increased and hit peak between 2020-Jun and 2020-Aug. and then decrease and hit low again in 2020-Dec and increased again after that. In the following order, 6-3-5-1-3-(7,2), the later cluster number is, the more entertainment attendance decreased between 2020-Oct and 2021-Feb. Hawaii, which singly clustered as cluster 6, entertainment attendance increase significantly between 2020-Oct and 2021-Feb probably because it’s the typical travel season of Hawaii. In the following order: 5-1-2-(4,6)-3-7, the later cluster number is in the order, the more entertainment attendance increased during 2020-Jun to 2020-Apr peak compared with time before COVID-19.

For employment population ratio, almost all states hit the worst employment-population-ratio in April and the situation got improved gradually after that. The Following order of cluster numbers shows how badly employment-population ratio were affected by COVID-19: 1 - (3,6,4) - 2- 5. The later cluster number is, the more employment-population ratio generally decreased after 2020-Apr and are more likely the states still struggle more than others in solving unemployment issue right now. We can see for example, Hawaii, Nevada, California, New York are in the clusters that have the biggest drop in employment while some states like Utah, Wyoming’s employment were not affected a lot by COVID-19. Other clusters, compared with cluster 4 and 6, show bigger improvement in employment when comparing the current situation with the worst time in April.

For house days on market, interestingly, for almost all states, house days on market gradually decreased after 2020-Apr, the reason for this is probably people’s concern about economic inflation due to COVID-19. In the following order: 7-3-(5,6)-4-1-2, the later cluster number is in the order, the more house days on market dropped between 2020-May and 2020-Jun compared to before-covid time. Cluster 6 (State of Idaho), has the biggest drop for house days on market in the beginning of 2021 compared to 2020-Apr. Cluster 5 and 7, in contrast, had relatively little change of house days on market when comparing year 2021 to 2020-Apr.

For house new listings, most states had a big decrease of house new listing in 2020-Apr, and gradually got back in normal or even better than before-covid time. In the following order: 5-1-3-2-4, the later cluster number is in the order, the more house new listing got back to normal or increased after 2020-Oct. Moreover, in 2020-Apr, states Pennsylvania, New Jersey, New York, Connecticut, Michigan, Vermont, Utah had the smallest negative effect by COVID-19 in terms of house new listing, whereas Arkansas, Tennessee, Kansas, Wisconsin, Minnesota ‘s house new listing decreased the most in 2020-Apr.

For flight departure delay, almost all states saw a big drop in average aviation departure delay after COVID-19, and the low average aviation departure delay had lasted for almost all year in 2020 but had a trend of returning to normal at the beginning of 2021. In the following order: 5-3-2-1-4. The later cluster number is in the order, the more likely that in late 2020, the average aviation delay of that state was still much lower than that of before COVID-19 time.

For gasoline consumption, most states saw a big drop of gasoline consumption around 2020-Apr and a trend of returning to normal around 2020-Jun. However, gasoline consumption of most states haven’t return to the normal situation. And in the following order: 5-2-3-4-1, the later cluster number is in the order, the more likely that between 2020-May and 2020-Sep, the gasoline consumption either had a big drop in 2020-May but return to normal soon or the consumption of gasoline had a drop in 2020-May and have not returned to normal and was still less in 2020-Oct compared to before-covid time.
